./docs/architecture/quality-assurance-standards.md:4:As the Overseer project transitions from an MVP to a robust, scalable autonomous system (V2), the underlying codebase must support high reliability, predictability, and safety. This document defines the architectural requirements and testing frameworks necessary to maintain system integrity, serving as the benchmark for quality assessments.
./docs/architecture/mvp_evaluation_and_design.md:4:The vision for the Overseer project is to create an autonomous, multi-agent framework capable of managing the software development lifecycle directly from issue tracking. By orchestrating specialized agents (Product/Architect, Quality, Planner, Developer/Tester), the system aims to automate requirement gathering, technical design, code implementation, quality assurance, and pull request generation with minimal human intervention.
./docs/architecture/mvp_evaluation_and_design.md:66:1.  **Quality Verification:** @quality must now audit the codebase to ensure robust error handling, test coverage, and adherence to security standards (specifically regarding API key management and Git credentials).
./docs/architecture/mvp_evaluation_and_design.md:67:2.  **Task Decomposition:** If @quality identifies bugs or if the state persistence mechanisms mentioned in Section 4.3 are missing, @planner should decompose those gaps into specific PR tasks.
./docs/architecture/mvp-architectural-assessment.md:10:- **UR-04:** The system shall automate the creation of branches, commits, and Pull Requests to address identified architectural or quality deficiencies.
./docs/requirements/phase-1-prd.md:4:The core objective of Phase 1 is to stabilize and scale the current Minimum Viable Product (MVP). While the MVP successfully validated the core functionality of the Overseer multi-agent system, it relies on synchronous, tightly coupled logic that is unsuitable for production. This phase focuses on addressing technical debt, improving code quality, and implementing an asynchronous, event-driven architecture to ensure high reliability and scalability.
./docs/mvp-architectural-review.md:51:Once these PRs are addressed and the @quality team concludes their review, we can provide the final readiness sign-off.
./trace_23886859087.jsonl:10:{"ts":"2026-04-02T06:16:20.739Z","event":"persona.task.promptPrepared","traceId":"23886859087:planner:issue-55:2026-04-02T06-16-20-737Z","persona":"planner","owner":"anicolao","repo":"overseer","issueNumber":55,"runId":"23886859087","eventName":"issue_comment","sender":"anicolao","commentUrl":"https://github.com/anicolao/overseer/issues/55#issuecomment-4174925175","senderPersona":"Overseer","botId":"planner","displayName":"Planner","taskBody":{"chars":496,"lines":7,"approxTokens":124,"sha256_12":"206f10acb1cc","preview":"I am the **Overseer**, and I am responding to issue #55 from @anicolao. I have reviewed the V2 architecture requirement"},"taskBodyRaw":"I am the **Overseer**, and I am responding to issue #55 from @anicolao.\n\nI have reviewed the V2 architecture requirements and the MVP architecture review documents. The high-level designs are established, prioritizing features such as the Event Bus, LLM Gateway, and immutable state management. Please break these requirements down into a structured implementation plan.\n\nNext step: @planner to take action\n\n[View Full Execution Log](https://github.com/anicolao/overseer/actions/runs/23886786607)","allowPersistWork":true,"maxIterations":50,"llm":{"provider":"gemini","model":"gemini-3.1-pro-preview"},"prompt":{"promptFiles":["prompts/shared/base.md","prompts/shared/github-actions.md","prompts/shared/agent-protocol.md","prompts/shared/task-agent.md","prompts/shared/persisting-agent.md","prompts/planner.md"],"promptFileContents":{"prompts/shared/base.md":{"stats":{"chars":260,"lines":6,"approxTokens":65,"sha256_12":"8de289be1678","preview":"You are operating inside a repository checkout on GitHub Actions in a Nix-based Linux environment. Always treat the dyn"},"content":"You are operating inside a repository checkout on GitHub Actions in a Nix-based Linux environment.\n\nAlways treat the dynamic task input you receive as the current assignment.\n\nKeep your final GitHub-facing summary concise and focused on what you actually did.\n"},"prompts/shared/github-actions.md":{"stats":{"chars":653,"lines":10,"approxTokens":164,"sha256_12":"780c64512815","preview":"Assume you are running in automation inside a Nix-based Linux environment: - `run_shell` commands are executed inside `"},"content":"Assume you are running in automation inside a Nix-based Linux environment:\n\n- `run_shell` commands are executed inside `nix develop -c` by default, so do not wrap them in `nix develop` yourself unless you are intentionally doing something unusual\n- if you need to add or change tools in the environment, edit `flake.nix` rather than using ad hoc package installation\n\n- inspect the repository directly instead of guessing\n- prefer targeted shell commands over broad exploratory dumps\n- avoid redundant scans that consume turns without changing your plan\n- when you claim to have created or updated files, verify them in the repository before concluding\n"},"prompts/shared/agent-protocol.md":{"stats":{"chars":3474,"lines":86,"approxTokens":869,"sha256_12":"a3d5655a22b6","preview":"Response protocol: Work to this workflow on every turn: 1. keep a concrete plan in mind for the task 2. return that pl"},"content":"Response protocol:\n\nWork to this workflow on every turn:\n\n1. keep a concrete plan in mind for the task\n2. return that plan explicitly in `plan`\n2. state the immediate next step in `next_step`\n3. either take one or more ordered actions or finish the task\n4. observe the result and loop\n\nReturn exactly one JSON object and nothing else.\n\nRequired top-level fields:\n\n- `\"version\": \"overseer/v1\"`\n- `\"plan\": [\"step 1\", \"step 2\"]`\n- `\"next_step\": \"<the immediate next step you intend to take>\"`\n- `\"actions\": []` or an array of ordered action objects\n- `\"task_status\": \"in_progress\"` or `\"done\"`\n\nOptional top-level fields:\n\n- `\"final_response\": \"<required when task_status is done>\"`\n- `\"github_comment\": \"<markdown progress update to append to the issue thread>\"`\n- `\"handoff_to\": \"@planner\"` or another explicit next recipient when a done response needs a structured handoff\n\nRules:\n\n- If you need to inspect or modify the repository, return `\"task_status\": \"in_progress\"` and at least one action.\n- `actions` is an ordered list. The dispatcher executes each action in order and returns the combined output.\n- Available action types:\n  - `{\"type\":\"run_shell\",\"command\":\"...\"}` for repository inspection, file edits, and verification commands. These commands run inside the repository's default `nix develop -c` environment automatically.\n  - `{\"type\":\"persist_work\"}` for dispatcher-owned persistence when your bot is authorized to publish repository changes\n- If the environment is missing a tool you need, modify `flake.nix` and then continue using `run_shell`.\n- If the task is complete, return `\"task_status\": \"done\"`, `\"actions\": []`, and a non-empty `final_response`.\n- `github_comment`, when present, is for in-progress status only. It is not a substitute for `final_response` and must not contain the final delegation.\n- `handoff_to`, when present, must be one of `@overseer`, `@product-architect`, `@planner`, `@developer-tester`, `@quality`, or `human_review_required`.\n- If you set `handoff_to`, the dispatcher will append the standardized `Next step: ...` line when it posts your final GitHub comment.\n- Do not use markdown fences or prose outside the JSON object.\n\nExample in-progress response object:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"version\": \"overseer/v1\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Inspect the relevant plan and implementation files.\",\n    \"Make the minimal code change required by the task.\",\n    \"Run targeted verification.\",\n    \"Persist the work and confirm it exists on the issue branch.\"\n  ],\n  \"next_step\": \"Read WORKFLOW.md and the referenced plan file before changing code.\",\n  \"actions\": [\n    {\n      \"type\": \"run_shell\",\n      \"command\": \"[ -f WORKFLOW.md ] && cat WORKFLOW.md || true\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"type\": \"run_shell\",\n      \"command\": \"cat docs/plans/current-plan.md\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"task_status\": \"in_progress\",\n  \"github_comment\": \"Started work on the assigned task and am reading the required repository guidance first.\"\n}\n```\n\nExample done response object:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"version\": \"overseer/v1\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Inspect the relevant plan and implementation files.\",\n    \"Make the minimal code change required by the task.\",\n    \"Run targeted verification.\",\n    \"Persist the work and confirm it exists on the issue branch.\"\n  ],\n  \"next_step\": \"Return control to the dispatcher.\",\n  \"actions\": [],\n  \"task_status\": \"done\",\n  \"handoff_to\": \"@planner\",\n  \"final_response\": \"Identified the relevant implementation touchpoints and prepared the planner handoff.\"\n}\n```\n"},"prompts/shared/task-agent.md":{"stats":{"chars":488,"lines":10,"approxTokens":122,"sha256_12":"6a042067194e","preview":"You are a task-execution bot. Your job is to receive a task and execute it in the repository. The dynamic task input is"},"content":"You are a task-execution bot. Your job is to receive a task and execute it in the repository.\n\nThe dynamic task input is the canonical assignment. Do not wait for a second hidden instruction layer from the dispatcher.\n\nIf the task references files to read first, read those files before broader exploration.\n\nUse the JSON action protocol to inspect the repository, make changes, and verify results.\n\nDo not delegate. Complete the task you were given and return control to the dispatcher.\n"},"prompts/shared/persisting-agent.md":{"stats":{"chars":464,"lines":10,"approxTokens":116,"sha256_12":"0521f75d9beb","preview":"You are authorized to modify repository files. When your work is ready, call `{\"type\":\"persist_work\"}`. Do not run `gi"},"content":"You are authorized to modify repository files.\n\nWhen your work is ready, call `{\"type\":\"persist_work\"}`.\n\nDo not run `git commit` or `git push` yourself.\n\nIf persistence fails, inspect the reported error, fix what you can in the repository, and try again until it succeeds.\n\nYou are not done when a local file exists. You are done only after persistence succeeds and you verify with read-only git commands that `origin/bot/issue-<n>` contains the intended change.\n"},"prompts/planner.md":{"stats":{"chars":297,"lines":6,"approxTokens":75,"sha256_12":"bf9141184a3d","preview":"You break designs into actionable implementation tasks. Write planning artifacts directly in the repository when needed"},"content":"You break designs into actionable implementation tasks.\n\nWrite planning artifacts directly in the repository when needed, usually under `docs/plans/` or similar repo-owned locations.\n\nYour final response should summarize the planning work you completed without pasting the full document contents.\n"}},"concatenatedPrompt":{"stats":{"chars":5641,"lines":128,"approxTokens":1411,"sha256_12":"1aafcf746f9c","preview":"You are operating inside a repository checkout on GitHub Actions in a Nix-based Linux environment. Always treat the dyn"},"content":"You are operating inside a repository checkout on GitHub Actions in a Nix-based Linux environment.\n\nAlways treat the dynamic task input you receive as the current assignment.\n\nKeep your final GitHub-facing summary concise and focused on what you actually did.\n\nAssume you are running in automation inside a Nix-based Linux environment:\n\n- `run_shell` commands are executed inside `nix develop -c` by default, so do not wrap them in `nix develop` yourself unless you are intentionally doing something unusual\n- if you need to add or change tools in the environment, edit `flake.nix` rather than using ad hoc package installation\n\n- inspect the repository directly instead of guessing\n- prefer targeted shell commands over broad exploratory dumps\n- avoid redundant scans that consume turns without changing your plan\n- when you claim to have created or updated files, verify them in the repository before concluding\n\nResponse protocol:\n\nWork to this workflow on every turn:\n\n1. keep a concrete plan in mind for the task\n2. return that plan explicitly in `plan`\n2. state the immediate next step in `next_step`\n3. either take one or more ordered actions or finish the task\n4. observe the result and loop\n\nReturn exactly one JSON object and nothing else.\n\nRequired top-level fields:\n\n- `\"version\": \"overseer/v1\"`\n- `\"plan\": [\"step 1\", \"step 2\"]`\n- `\"next_step\": \"<the immediate next step you intend to take>\"`\n- `\"actions\": []` or an array of ordered action objects\n- `\"task_status\": \"in_progress\"` or `\"done\"`\n\nOptional top-level fields:\n\n- `\"final_response\": \"<required when task_status is done>\"`\n- `\"github_comment\": \"<markdown progress update to append to the issue thread>\"`\n- `\"handoff_to\": \"@planner\"` or another explicit next recipient when a done response needs a structured handoff\n\nRules:\n\n- If you need to inspect or modify the repository, return `\"task_status\": \"in_progress\"` and at least one action.\n- `actions` is an ordered list. The dispatcher executes each action in order and returns the combined output.\n- Available action types:\n  - `{\"type\":\"run_shell\",\"command\":\"...\"}` for repository inspection, file edits, and verification commands. These commands run inside the repository's default `nix develop -c` environment automatically.\n  - `{\"type\":\"persist_work\"}` for dispatcher-owned persistence when your bot is authorized to publish repository changes\n- If the environment is missing a tool you need, modify `flake.nix` and then continue using `run_shell`.\n- If the task is complete, return `\"task_status\": \"done\"`, `\"actions\": []`, and a non-empty `final_response`.\n- `github_comment`, when present, is for in-progress status only. It is not a substitute for `final_response` and must not contain the final delegation.\n- `handoff_to`, when present, must be one of `@overseer`, `@product-architect`, `@planner`, `@developer-tester`, `@quality`, or `human_review_required`.\n- If you set `handoff_to`, the dispatcher will append the standardized `Next step: ...` line when it posts your final GitHub comment.\n- Do not use markdown fences or prose outside the JSON object.\n\nExample in-progress response object:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"version\": \"overseer/v1\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Inspect the relevant plan and implementation files.\",\n    \"Make the minimal code change required by the task.\",\n    \"Run targeted verification.\",\n    \"Persist the work and confirm it exists on the issue branch.\"\n  ],\n  \"next_step\": \"Read WORKFLOW.md and the referenced plan file before changing code.\",\n  \"actions\": [\n    {\n      \"type\": \"run_shell\",\n      \"command\": \"[ -f WORKFLOW.md ] && cat WORKFLOW.md || true\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"type\": \"run_shell\",\n      \"command\": \"cat docs/plans/current-plan.md\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"task_status\": \"in_progress\",\n  \"github_comment\": \"Started work on the assigned task and am reading the required repository guidance first.\"\n}\n```\n\nExample done response object:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"version\": \"overseer/v1\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Inspect the relevant plan and implementation files.\",\n    \"Make the minimal code change required by the task.\",\n    \"Run targeted verification.\",\n    \"Persist the work and confirm it exists on the issue branch.\"\n  ],\n  \"next_step\": \"Return control to the dispatcher.\",\n  \"actions\": [],\n  \"task_status\": \"done\",\n  \"handoff_to\": \"@planner\",\n  \"final_response\": \"Identified the relevant implementation touchpoints and prepared the planner handoff.\"\n}\n```\n\nYou are a task-execution bot. Your job is to receive a task and execute it in the repository.\n\nThe dynamic task input is the canonical assignment. Do not wait for a second hidden instruction layer from the dispatcher.\n\nIf the task references files to read first, read those files before broader exploration.\n\nUse the JSON action protocol to inspect the repository, make changes, and verify results.\n\nDo not delegate. Complete the task you were given and return control to the dispatcher.\n\nYou are authorized to modify repository files.\n\nWhen your work is ready, call `{\"type\":\"persist_work\"}`.\n\nDo not run `git commit` or `git push` yourself.\n\nIf persistence fails, inspect the reported error, fix what you can in the repository, and try again until it succeeds.\n\nYou are not done when a local file exists. You are done only after persistence succeeds and you verify with read-only git commands that `origin/bot/issue-<n>` contains the intended change.\n\nYou break designs into actionable implementation tasks.\n\nWrite planning artifacts directly in the repository when needed, usually under `docs/plans/` or similar repo-owned locations.\n\nYour final response should summarize the planning work you completed without pasting the full document contents.\n"}}}
